1567
01:35:36.017 --> 01:35:39.838
consulted on out through engagement with disability communities and

1568
01:35:39.897 --> 01:35:43.458
then written into both the framework in detail interlinked?

1569
01:35:43.798 --> 01:35:45.778
The devil's always in the detail. We know this.

1570
01:35:46.778 --> 01:35:49.158
We've dealt with policies over the years.

1571
01:35:49.718 --> 01:35:52.098
And so yes, we do need to know what the detail is.

1572
01:35:52.618 --> 01:35:56.238
It is very disturbing having that secondary layer. We don't know what's coming.

1573
01:35:56.318 --> 01:35:58.338
We don't know how it's going to be interpreted.

1574
01:35:58.378 --> 01:36:02.198
And while this m- this minister may have the very best of intentions, five

1575
01:36:02.218 --> 01:36:05.338
years down the track, 10 years down the track, when you have-- you've got your

1576
01:36:05.378 --> 01:36:08.318
lovely pensions and you're sitting there thinking about what you did in the past,

1577
01:36:08.838 --> 01:36:11.198
we are the ones fighting for it. No.

1578
01:36:11.258 --> 01:36:12.858
We've got to know now what's what.

1579
01:36:13.438 --> 01:36:14.618
Mm. Thank you.

1580
01:36:14.658 --> 01:36:17.818
Thank you, Colleen. I should just say, parliamentarians don't get pensions

1581
01:36:18.538 --> 01:36:21.738
any different than any other citizen does. Just for the record.

1582
01:36:22.698 --> 01:36:25.718
But point taken. Thank- thanks for making your submission.

1583
01:36:26.478 --> 01:36:27.148
You're welcome.

1584
01:36:27.148 --> 01:36:27.378
You're welcome.

1585
01:36:27.458 --> 01:36:28.618
Unless you're paying.

1586
01:36:30.618 --> 01:36:31.988
All right. Do we have-

1587
01:36:32.008 --> 01:36:32.478
More things.

1588
01:36:33.818 --> 01:36:34.038
Yeah.

1589
01:36:34.878 --> 01:36:35.218
Linda.

1590
01:36:36.038 --> 01:36:36.818
Okay, Linda.

1591
01:36:38.078 --> 01:36:55.698
Sorry.

1592
01:36:55.738 --> 01:36:56.078
Just getting-

1593
01:36:56.178 --> 01:36:59.978
Oh. Oh, there we go. We can see you loud and clear, and we can hear you nice and

1594
01:37:00.018 --> 01:37:03.188
clearly as well. Welcome, Linda. Thanks for appearing for our committee this

1595
01:37:03.238 --> 01:37:04.478
afternoon. The time is yours when you're ready.

1596
01:37:05.078 --> 01:37:05.538
Thank you.

1597
01:37:06.998 --> 01:37:10.978
I have a few points to make, and I'm happy to take questions because you've read

1598
01:37:11.038 --> 01:37:13.558
my statement. So,

1599
01:37:14.698 --> 01:37:17.598
first of all, I just want to make the point that families of people with

1600
01:37:17.638 --> 01:37:21.538
disabilities are some of the very hardest working people in Aotearoa.

1601
01:37:22.118 --> 01:37:24.198
We often think that farmers are hardworking.

1602
01:37:24.258 --> 01:37:27.838
Tell you what, families of people with disabilities work a whole lot more

1603
01:37:28.138 --> 01:37:31.806
as well as that. And it doesn't stop As

1604
01:37:31.826 --> 01:37:34.726
families will have told you, there is no retirement age.

1605
01:37:34.846 --> 01:37:38.666
There is no three weeks off or any weeks off in a year.

1606
01:37:38.746 --> 01:37:42.646
You can't just step away from it. And families stay connected

1607
01:37:42.966 --> 01:37:45.206
regardless of what else happens around.

1608
01:37:45.766 --> 01:37:48.686
So they know their responsibilities and they don't shirk from them.

1609
01:37:49.886 --> 01:37:53.556
It's rather disingenuous to suggest that this is a new idea, that

1610
01:37:53.606 --> 01:37:57.386
families should take responsibility, and it feels rather insulting to

1611
01:37:57.446 --> 01:38:01.166
families who are there day in, day out, 24/7,

1612
01:38:01.786 --> 01:38:05.506
regardless of what else happens. I've been a sibling, am a

1613
01:38:05.566 --> 01:38:09.526
sibling, and a grandmother, and so I can tell you, it

1614
01:38:09.746 --> 01:38:13.046
is a commitment, a long-term, lifetime commitment,

1615
01:38:13.686 --> 01:38:16.906
and families live up to that. It's hard work.

1616
01:38:17.406 --> 01:38:18.526
As people will tell you,

1617
01:38:19.486 --> 01:38:23.466
it often means stepping aside from other opportunities and committing

1618
01:38:23.566 --> 01:38:27.526
to family members. So what families seek is consistency and support

1619
01:38:27.566 --> 01:38:30.286
from government, and that can be hard to come by.

1620
01:38:30.966 --> 01:38:33.806
Consistency means knowing what's coming next.

1621
01:38:34.486 --> 01:38:35.366
When things change

1622
01:38:36.746 --> 01:38:40.266
often, as they do, that makes life more difficult than it needs to

1623
01:38:40.306 --> 01:38:44.246
be. So my reading of the purposes of this bill is to limit

1624
01:38:44.286 --> 01:38:45.596
financial risk to government,

1625
01:38:46.446 --> 01:38:49.156
to establish a three-year pathway to get legislation

1626
01:38:50.066 --> 01:38:52.656
framework, and to manage DSS budgets.

1627
01:38:52.786 --> 01:38:56.106
Now, I can relate to some of that. It is important.

1628
01:38:57.566 --> 01:39:01.546
However, I would suggest that it's time to acknowledge that there

1629
01:39:01.626 --> 01:39:05.146
is a need for increases in funding within

1630
01:39:05.186 --> 01:39:08.276
DSS budget. It just isn't enough, and it hasn't been enough for some

1631
01:39:08.326 --> 01:39:12.126
time. So in developing frameworks going

1632
01:39:12.186 --> 01:39:13.986
forward, this needs to be kept in mind,

1633
01:39:15.046 --> 01:39:18.946
and I would suggest that families need to

1634
01:39:18.986 --> 01:39:20.046
have a voice in that,

1635
01:39:20.966 --> 01:39:22.966
as do people with disabilities.

1636
01:39:23.846 --> 01:39:27.386
Because without this being done in a thoughtful

1637
01:39:27.506 --> 01:39:27.856
way,

1638
01:39:28.946 --> 01:39:29.246
the

1639
01:39:31.406 --> 01:39:34.646
out costs will be far more expensive for government.

1640
01:39:35.126 --> 01:39:39.066
I have seen how when these costs are cost shifted to

1641
01:39:39.126 --> 01:39:40.746
other parts of government, and they will be,

1642
01:39:41.766 --> 01:39:43.286
it actually costs a whole lot more.

1643
01:39:43.346 --> 01:39:47.136
So investment now and upfront in a meaningful way would be a better

1644
01:39:47.206 --> 01:39:50.526
outcome, I would suggest. I'm happy to take questions.

1645
01:39:51.706 --> 01:39:54.126
Mm. Thanks for that, Linda. Appreciate that.

1646
01:39:54.546 --> 01:39:58.366
Actually, just on that, a sort of question on my mind is, obviously,

1647
01:39:58.506 --> 01:40:01.726
this is about DSS-funded disability support services.

1648
01:40:02.286 --> 01:40:04.726
And I note Section 8 talks about

1649
01:40:06.746 --> 01:40:10.396
that the ministry or contract provider must take into account

1650
01:40:11.926 --> 01:40:14.306
other publicly funded sources as well as family

1651
01:40:15.246 --> 01:40:19.126
and as well as their community. So, I'm just wondering if you can just, from your

1652
01:40:19.146 --> 01:40:22.356
experience, just talk us a little bit through what the differences between the

1653
01:40:22.366 --> 01:40:26.346
DSS-funded services are and the other publicly funded services are that are sort

1654
01:40:26.386 --> 01:40:28.466
of typically accessed.

1655
01:40:28.506 --> 01:40:32.386
Well, obviously, education's one of the earlier ones in the life

1656
01:40:32.466 --> 01:40:36.155
of a child with a disability. When there are artificial

1657
01:40:36.266 --> 01:40:40.026
boundaries between that, then it can be a case of families trying to

1658
01:40:40.066 --> 01:40:43.486
battle between these services. And there should be a

1659
01:40:43.626 --> 01:40:47.546
linking up. So, where therapy is provided in

1660
01:40:47.586 --> 01:40:51.556
education and not in health or not in DSS, there's a tension

1661
01:40:51.586 --> 01:40:55.426
there. Those are services that need to link up more.

1662
01:40:56.026 --> 01:40:57.136
Equipment services,

1663
01:40:58.066 --> 01:41:01.666
when they stand alone, make life difficult for families to negotiate.

1664
01:41:01.706 --> 01:41:05.176
And DSS funding has a look across some of those,

1665
01:41:05.406 --> 01:41:08.806
but over time, we've created these boundaries between them.

1666
01:41:09.326 --> 01:41:11.206
I've seen in health where

1667
01:41:13.286 --> 01:41:17.066
DHB services or Ministry of Health services end up picking up

1668
01:41:17.446 --> 01:41:20.526
the shortfall when nothing else is available.

1669
01:41:20.586 --> 01:41:23.986
And so the cost in health is way more than a cost in

1670
01:41:24.026 --> 01:41:26.726
DSS. And so again, working together.

1671
01:41:26.846 --> 01:41:30.606
I know that there's at least 100 people sitting in hospital services now

1672
01:41:31.106 --> 01:41:34.426
who have a disability and don't belong in a mental health services,

1673
01:41:34.526 --> 01:41:38.106
but they're in the most expensive place they could ever be.

1674
01:41:38.776 --> 01:41:42.706
And so we need to work together. If DSS was able to

1675
01:41:42.726 --> 01:41:46.286
provide the support in the community, health would not be carrying that

1676
01:41:46.306 --> 01:41:50.086
burden. At the moment, we've cost shifted it into another place, a

1677
01:41:50.186 --> 01:41:51.946
really much more expensive place.

1678
01:41:52.386 --> 01:41:53.316
Adviser.

1679
01:41:53.446 --> 01:41:55.726
That was very helpful context, and I thank you for that.

1680
01:41:55.766 --> 01:41:58.406
And thank you again for making submission this afternoon.

1681
01:41:58.566 --> 01:41:59.146
Thank you.

1682
01:41:59.186 --> 01:41:59.646
Appreciate it.

1683
01:42:00.046 --> 01:42:01.606
Yeah. That's really

1684
01:42:01.826 --> 01:42:04.126
good.

1685
01:42:04.226 --> 01:42:05.186
We have Amy.

1686
01:42:07.906 --> 01:42:09.126
Amy? Great.

1687
01:42:21.726 --> 01:42:23.006
Good evening, Amy. Welcome.

1688
01:42:23.646 --> 01:42:24.166
Good morning.

1689
01:42:24.906 --> 01:42:27.126
Yep. No, we can hear and see you, so great.

1690
01:42:27.386 --> 01:42:28.545
The time is yours when you're ready to go.

1691
01:42:29.106 --> 01:42:29.586
Thank you.

1692
01:42:31.106 --> 01:42:32.786
So my name's Amy Taylor.

1693
01:42:33.886 --> 01:42:37.146
Multigenerational disability has shaped my life.

1694
01:42:38.546 --> 01:42:42.006
I'm a disabled person living with multiple sclerosis,

1695
01:42:42.586 --> 01:42:46.425
and I'm also autistic. These experiences shape how I move

1696
01:42:46.446 --> 01:42:49.126
through the world and what I'm showing up here for

1697
01:42:49.166 --> 01:42:53.066
today. I come from a line of disabled people.

1698
01:42:53.106 --> 01:42:56.056
So I grew up alongside my mother, a feisty,

1699
01:42:56.226 --> 01:43:00.046
unapologetically disabled woman living with advanced MS.

1700
01:43:00.786 --> 01:43:03.086
In my late teens, I became her carer.

1701
01:43:03.886 --> 01:43:05.726
This was the late 1990s,

1702
01:43:06.766 --> 01:43:10.686
when the lack of a lot of disability support services meant

1703
01:43:10.746 --> 01:43:12.266
that we were put in that position.

1704
01:43:13.246 --> 01:43:16.786
That experience has had a lasting impact on my education,

1705
01:43:17.286 --> 01:43:20.486
my income, and the career choices available to me.

1706
01:43:21.156 --> 01:43:24.756
It also put significant strain on my mum and I's relationship,

1707
01:43:25.126 --> 01:43:29.026
which became really unhealthy for a long time.

1708
01:43:29.066 --> 01:43:32.406
Today, I work three days a week. This is what I can

1709
01:43:32.446 --> 01:43:36.426
sustainably manage, and if I work more, I enter cycles of

1710
01:43:36.466 --> 01:43:40.066
burnout and symptom flare-ups that render me completely useless.

1711
01:43:41.222 --> 01:43:44.802
I'm also raising two disabled children with complex health

1712
01:43:44.902 --> 01:43:48.482
needs. They can't attend school full-time,

1713
01:43:49.042 --> 01:43:52.302
but they're curious, bright, motivated to learn.

1714
01:43:52.342 --> 01:43:54.532
They want to contribute to society.

1715
01:43:55.042 --> 01:43:58.442
They just can't do it at the pace that non-disabled people are

1716
01:43:58.502 --> 01:44:02.032
expected to. And when I look at their future, I feel really

1717
01:44:02.082 --> 01:44:02.642
worried,

1718
01:44:03.662 --> 01:44:07.022
because this bill assumes something that my life tells me is not true.

1719
01:44:07.742 --> 01:44:10.542
It assumes that families can carry the load.

1720
01:44:11.352 --> 01:44:15.142
This bill places responsibility for care first on whānau

1721
01:44:15.502 --> 01:44:19.482
and reinforces ideas of natural supports, but I've lived what that

1722
01:44:19.522 --> 01:44:22.942
looks like. It looks like children becoming

1723
01:44:23.042 --> 01:44:26.882
carers. It looks like intergenerational poverty.

1724
01:44:27.542 --> 01:44:31.362
It looks like people having to choose between their health and their economic

1725
01:44:31.422 --> 01:44:32.002
survival.

1726
01:44:32.922 --> 01:44:36.562
Because when the state steps back, someone else carries the cost,

1727
01:44:36.962 --> 01:44:40.522
and that cost is already being carried by

1728
01:44:40.582 --> 01:44:42.402
disabled people and their families.

1729
01:44:43.262 --> 01:44:47.152
It frames disability support as a contribution, not as a right,

1730
01:44:47.602 --> 01:44:50.922
not as an entitlement. That matters, because a

1731
01:44:51.002 --> 01:44:54.942
contribution can be reduced, a contribution can be withheld.

1732
01:44:55.402 --> 01:44:58.602
A contribution does not guarantee dignity.

1733
01:44:59.442 --> 01:45:03.262
But disabled people's lives and wellbeing should not depend on what is

1734
01:45:03.322 --> 01:45:06.241
left over. It is a matter of human rights.

1735
01:45:07.682 --> 01:45:11.502
We've recently had Supreme Court recognition that some family carers

1736
01:45:11.562 --> 01:45:15.062
are workers. It acknowledged the real labor of care.

1737
01:45:15.682 --> 01:45:18.222
This bill moves away from that recognition.

1738
01:45:19.062 --> 01:45:22.962
I have lived that work. I still do. It is constant, it is

1739
01:45:23.022 --> 01:45:26.242
highly skilled, and it shapes entire lives.

1740
01:45:27.262 --> 01:45:30.102
I've serious concerns about how this bill is structured.

1741
01:45:30.762 --> 01:45:34.602
Much of the real decision-making, who gets support, what they

1742
01:45:34.642 --> 01:45:38.362
receive, and how is left to regulations rather than the bill

1743
01:45:38.422 --> 01:45:41.612
itself. This creates too much uncertainty.

1744
01:45:42.342 --> 01:45:46.202
It means the rules that shape my life can change without

1745
01:45:46.302 --> 01:45:50.182
meaningful scrutiny and without disabled people being meaningfully

1746
01:45:50.222 --> 01:45:50.851
involved,

1747
01:45:51.742 --> 01:45:55.502
and many in our community already feel that consultation has been lacking.

1748
01:45:56.462 --> 01:45:59.702
Finally, I want to speak plainly about independence.

1749
01:46:00.482 --> 01:46:04.122
When support systems rely more heavily on family, they

1750
01:46:04.182 --> 01:46:07.982
assume those families are safe and able to provide care,

1751
01:46:08.342 --> 01:46:12.242
and that is not always true. Not all disabled people have safe

1752
01:46:12.322 --> 01:46:16.082
or supportive whānau, and when survival is tied to

1753
01:46:16.142 --> 01:46:19.522
family or partners, people can be forced into

1754
01:46:19.582 --> 01:46:22.262
unsafe or abusive situations.

1755
01:46:23.171 --> 01:46:26.842
That is a loss of independence. It is a loss of choice,

1756
01:46:27.242 --> 01:46:31.062
and it is a human rights issue. Disabled people

1757
01:46:31.072 --> 01:46:33.722
need to be seen as having inherent value.

1758
01:46:34.702 --> 01:46:38.442
When you're not worrying about how you're going to feed yourself that week, you can

1759
01:46:38.522 --> 01:46:41.862
use your strengths to contribute meaningfully to communities.

1760
01:46:42.742 --> 01:46:44.902
That is what a good support system should do.

1761
01:46:45.902 --> 01:46:49.522
I want my children to grow up in a system that recognizes their value,

1762
01:46:49.982 --> 01:46:53.962
supports their independence, and does not limit their future

1763
01:46:54.082 --> 01:46:57.802
based on how much they can work or how much their family can carry.

1764
01:46:59.162 --> 01:47:03.122
A disability support services legal framework is needed, but this

1765
01:47:03.162 --> 01:47:06.862
bill in its current form should be withdrawn and redrafted in

1766
01:47:06.962 --> 01:47:08.082
genuine partnership.

1767
01:47:09.042 --> 01:47:11.342
What disabled people need is certainty.

1768
01:47:11.842 --> 01:47:15.822
We need our rights, as outlined by the United Nations Convention on the

1769
01:47:15.902 --> 01:47:19.611
Rights of Persons with Disabilities, to be strengthened, protected,

1770
01:47:19.762 --> 01:47:23.342
embedded in legislation so that they are not put at risk by

1771
01:47:23.402 --> 01:47:25.082
changing political parties.

1772
01:47:29.402 --> 01:47:31.462
All right. Great. No, thank you very much, Amy.

1773
01:47:31.502 --> 01:47:33.322
I appreciate you coming and making a submission

1774
01:47:34.262 --> 01:47:37.602
to the committee this evening and sharing the experience of you and your family.

1775
01:47:38.262 --> 01:47:39.262
Thank you.

1776
